In a **`.md` file**, leading spaces at the start of a line are tricky—Markdown normally **ignores them** unless you use a specific trick. 
Here are the **clean, correct ways** to get space at the beginning of a line:

---

### ✅ 1. Use `&nbsp;` (most practical for README)

```md id="1r5p1a"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Indented line
```

👉 Works everywhere (GitHub, docs, etc.)
👉 You control how much space by repeating `&nbsp;`

---

### ✅ 2. Use code block (for exact spacing)

```md
    Indented line
```

or:

````md
```txt
    Indented line
```
````

👉 Preserves spacing exactly
👉 But renders as **code**, not normal text

---

### ✅ 3. Use blockquote (visual indent)

```md id="azj7wg"
> Indented-like text
```

👉 Not real spaces, but looks indented

---

### ✅ 4. Use HTML `<pre>` (full control)

```md id="g5ax34"
<pre>
    Indented exactly
</pre>
```

---

### ⚠️ Important truth

```md id="nbazea"
    This will NOT work normally
```

👉 Plain spaces at line start are ignored unless Markdown treats it as a code block.

---

### 💡 What you should use (real-world)

* Writing README → **`&nbsp;`**
* Showing code → **code block**
* Structuring content → **lists / blockquotes**

